<p>In this exercise we will investigate a simple stochastic (probabilistic) model of recovery from an infection and the time <span class="tex"><mjx-container class="MathJax CtxtMenu_Attached_0" jax="SVG" role="presentation" style="position: relative;" tabindex="0" ctxtmenu_counter="223"><svg style="vertical-align: -0.029ex;" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="1.17ex" height="1.005ex" role="img" focusable="false" viewBox="0 -431 517 444" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" aria-hidden="true"><g stroke="currentColor" fill="currentColor" stroke-width="0" transform="matrix(1 0 0 -1 0 0)"><g data-mml-node="math"><g data-mml-node="mi"><use xlink:href="#MJX-TEX-I-1D70F"></use></g></g></g></svg><mjx-assistive-mml role="presentation" unselectable="on" display="inline"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mi>Ï</mi></math></mjx-assistive-mml></mjx-container></span> needed to recover. Although this model can be easily studied analytically using probability theory, we will instead use computational methods. (If you know about this distribution already, try to ignore what you know about it!)</p>
<p>In this model, an individual who is infected has a constant probability <span class="tex"><mjx-container class="MathJax CtxtMenu_Attached_0" jax="SVG" role="presentation" style="position: relative;" tabindex="0" ctxtmenu_counter="224"><svg style="vertical-align: -0.439ex;" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="1.138ex" height="1.439ex" role="img" focusable="false" viewBox="0 -442 503 636" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" aria-hidden="true"><g stroke="currentColor" fill="currentColor" stroke-width="0" transform="matrix(1 0 0 -1 0 0)"><g data-mml-node="math"><g data-mml-node="mi"><use xlink:href="#MJX-TEX-I-1D45D"></use></g></g></g></svg><mjx-assistive-mml role="presentation" unselectable="on" display="inline"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mi>p</mi></math></mjx-assistive-mml></mjx-container></span> to recover each day. If they recover on day <span class="tex"><mjx-container class="MathJax CtxtMenu_Attached_0" jax="SVG" role="presentation" style="position: relative;" tabindex="0" ctxtmenu_counter="225"><svg style="vertical-align: -0.025ex;" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="1.357ex" height="1.025ex" role="img" focusable="false" viewBox="0 -442 600 453" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" aria-hidden="true"><g stroke="currentColor" fill="currentColor" stroke-width="0" transform="matrix(1 0 0 -1 0 0)"><g data-mml-node="math"><g data-mml-node="mi"><use xlink:href="#MJX-TEX-I-1D45B"></use></g></g></g></svg><mjx-assistive-mml role="presentation" unselectable="on" display="inline"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mi>n</mi></math></mjx-assistive-mml></mjx-container></span> then <span class="tex"><mjx-container class="MathJax CtxtMenu_Attached_0" jax="SVG" role="presentation" style="position: relative;" tabindex="0" ctxtmenu_counter="226"><svg style="vertical-align: -0.029ex;" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="1.17ex" height="1.005ex" role="img" focusable="false" viewBox="0 -431 517 444" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" aria-hidden="true"><g stroke="currentColor" fill="currentColor" stroke-width="0" transform="matrix(1 0 0 -1 0 xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mi>Ï</mi></math></mjx-assistive-mml></mjx-container></span> takes the value <span class="tex"><mjx-container class="MathJax CtxtMenu_Attached_0" jax="SVG" role="presentation" style="position: relative;" tabindex="0" ctxtmenu_counter="227"><svg style="vertical-align: -0.025ex;" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="1.357ex" height="1.025ex" Each time we run a new experiment <span class="tex"><mjx-container class="MathJax CtxtMenu_Attached_0" jax="SVG" role="presentation" style="position: relative;" tabindex="0" ctxtmenu_counter="228"><svg style="vertical-align: -0.029ex;" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="1.17ex" height="1.005ex" role="img" focusable="false" viewBox="0 -431 517 444" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" aria-hidden="true"><g stroke="currentColor" fill="currentColor" stroke-width="0" transform="matrix(1 0 0 -1 0 0)"><g data-mml-node="math"><g data-mml-node="mi"><use xlink:href="#MJX-TEX-I-1D70F"></use></g></g></g></svg><mjx-assistive-mml role="presentation" unselectable="on" display="inline"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mi>Ï</mi></math></mjx-assistive-mml></mjx-container></span> will take on different values, so <span class="tex"><mjx-container class="MathJax CtxtMenu_Attached_0" jax="SVG" role="presentation" style="position: relative;" tabindex="0" ctxtmenu_counter="229"><svg style="vertical-align: -0.029ex;" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="1.17ex" height="1.005ex" role="img" focusable="false" viewBox="0 -431 517 444" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" aria-hidden="true"><g stroke="currentColor" fill="currentColor" stroke-width="0" transform="matrix(1 0 0 -1 0 0)"><g data-mml-node="math"><g data-mml-node="mi"><use xlink:href="#MJX-TEX-I-1D70F"></use></g></g></g></svg><mjx-assistive-mml role="presentation" unselectable="on" display="inline"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mi>Ï</mi></math></mjx-assistive-mml></mjx-container></span> is a (discrete) random variable. We thus need to study statistical properties of <span class="tex"><mjx-container class="MathJax CtxtMenu_Attached_0" jax="SVG" role="presentation" style="position: relative;" tabindex="0" ctxtmenu_counter="230"><svg style="vertical-align: -0.029ex;" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="1.17ex" height="1.005ex" role="img" focusable="false" viewBox="0 -431 517 444" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" aria-hidden="true"><g stroke="currentColor" fill="currentColor" stroke-width="0" transform="matrix(1 0 0 -1 0 0)"><g data-mml-node="math"><g data-mml-node="mi"><use xlink:href="#MJX-TEX-I-1D70F"></use></g></g></g></svg><mjx-assistive-mml role="presentation" unselectable="on" display="inline"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mi>Ï</mi></math></mjx-assistive-mml></mjx-container></span>, such as its mean and its probability distribution.</p>
<h4>Exercise 1.1 - <em>Probability distributions</em></h4>

<p>ð Write a function <code>frequencies(data)</code> that calculates and returns the frequencies (i.e. probability distribution) of input data.</p>
<p>The input will be an array of integers, <strong>with duplicates</strong>, and the result will be a dictionary that maps each occured value to its frequency in the data.</p>
<p>For example,</p>
<pre><code class="language-julia">frequencies([7, 8, 9, 7])</code></pre>
<p>should give</p>
<pre><code class="language-julia">Dict(
7 =&gt; 0.5,
8 =&gt; 0.25,
9 =&gt; 0.25
)</code></pre>
<p>As with any probability distribution, it should be normalised to <span class="tex"><mjx-container class="MathJax CtxtMenu_Attached_0" jax="SVG" role="presentation" style="position: relative;" tabindex="0" ctxtmenu_counter="260"><svg style="vertical-align: 0px;" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="1.131ex" height="1.507ex" role="img" focusable="false" viewBox="0 -666 500 666" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" aria-hidden="true"><g stroke="currentColor" fill="currentColor" stroke-width="0" transform="matrix(1 0 0 -1 0 0)"><g data-mml-node="math"><g data-mml-node="mn"><use xlink:href="#MJX-TEX-N-31"></use></g></g></g></svg><mjx-assistive-mml role="presentation" unselectable="on" display="inline"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mn>1</mn></math></mjx-assistive-mml></mjx-container></span>, in the sense that the <em>total</em> probability should be <span class="tex"><mjx-container class="MathJax CtxtMenu_Attached_0" jax="SVG" role="presentation" style="position: relative;" tabindex="0" ctxtmenu_counter="261"><svg style="vertical-align: 0px;" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="1.131ex" height="1.507ex" role="img" focusable="false" viewBox="0 -666 500 666" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" aria-hidden="true"><g stroke="currentColor" fill="currentColor" stroke-width="0" transform="matrix(1 0 0 -1 0 0)"><g data-mml-node="math"><g data-mml-node="mn"><use xlink:href="#MJX-TEX-N-31"></use></g></g></g></svg><mjx-assistive-mml role="presentation" unselectable="on" display="inline"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mn>1</mn></math></mjx-assistive-mml></mjx-container></span>.</p>

<h4>Exercise 1.4</h4>

<blockquote>
<h3>Note about plotting</h3>
<p>Plots.jl has an interesting property: a plot is an object, not an action. Functions like <code>plot</code>, <code>bar</code>, <code>histogram</code> don't draw anything on your screen - they just return a <code>Plots.Plot</code>. This is a struct that contains the <em>description</em> of a plot (what data should be plotted in what way?), not the <em>picture</em>.</p>
<p>So a Pluto cell with a single line, <code>plot(1:10)</code>, will show a plot, because the <em>result</em> of the function <code>plot</code> is a <code>Plot</code> object, and Pluto just shows the result of a cell.</p>
<h5>Modifying plots</h5>
<p>Nice plots are often formed by overlaying multiple plots. In Plots.jl, this is done using the <strong>modifying functions</strong>: <code>plot!</code>, <code>bar!</code>, <code>vline!</code>, etc. These take an extra (first) argument: a previous plot to modify.</p>
<p>For example, to plot the <code>sin</code>, <code>cos</code> and <code>tan</code> functions in the same view, we do:</p>
<pre><code class="language-julia">function sin_cos_plot()
T = -1.0:0.01:1.0
result = plot(T, sin.(T))
plot!(result, T, cos.(T))
plot!(result, T, tan.(T))
return result
end</code></pre>
<p>ð¡ This example demonstrates a useful pattern to combine plots:</p>
<ol>
<li><p>Create a <strong>new</strong> plot and store it in a variable</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Modify</strong> that plot to add more elements</p>
</li>
<li><p>Return the plot</p>
</li>
</ol>
<p>It is recommended that these 3 steps happen <strong>within a single cell</strong>. This can prevent some strange glitches when re-running cells. There are three ways to group expressions together into a single cell: <code>begin</code>, <code>let</code> and <code>function</code>. More on this <a href="#function_begin_let">later</a>!</p>
</blockquote>

<p>In this and the following exercises we will develop a simple stochastic model for combined infection and recovery in a population, which may exhibit an <strong>epidemic outbreak</strong> (i.e. a large spike in the number of infectious people). The population is <strong>well mixed</strong>, i.e. everyone is in contact with everyone else. [An example of this would be a small school or university in which people are constantly moving around and interacting with each other.]</p>
<p>The model is an <strong>individual-based</strong> or <strong>agent-based</strong> model: we explicitly keep track of each individual, or <strong>agent</strong>, in the population and their infection status. For the moment we will not keep track of their position in space; we will just assume that there is some mechanism, not included in the model, by which they interact with other individuals.</p>
<h4>Exercise 2.1</h4>
<p>Each agent will have its own <strong>internal state</strong>, modelling its infection status, namely "susceptible", "infectious" or "recovered". We would like to code these as values <code>S</code>, <code>I</code> and <code>R</code>, respectively. One way to do this is using an <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Enumerated_type"><strong>enumerated type</strong></a> or <strong>enum</strong>. Variables of this type can take only a pre-defined set of values; the Julia syntax is as follows:</p>

<p>ð Write a function <code>interact!</code> that takes an affected <code>agent</code> of type <code>Agent</code>, an <code>source</code> of type <code>Agent</code> and an <code>infection</code> of type <code>InfectionRecovery</code>. </li>

</li>

mime="text/html"><assignee></assignee><div><div class="markdown"><p>We used a <code>let</code> block in this cell to group multiple expressions together, but how is it different from <code>begin</code> or <code>function</code>?</p>
<span id="function_begin_let"></span>
<blockquote>
<h5><em><strong>function</strong></em> vs. <em><strong>begin</strong></em> vs. <em><strong>let</strong></em></h5>
<p>Writing functions is a way to group multiple expressions (i.e. lines of code) together into a mini-program. Note the following about functions:</p>
<ul>
<li><p>A function always returns <strong>one object</strong>.<a href="#footnote-1" class="footnote">[1]</a> This object can be given explicitly by writing <code>return x</code>, or implicitly: Julia functions always return the result of the last expression by default. So <code>f(x) = x+2</code> is the same as <code>f(x) = return x+2</code>.</p>
</li>
<li><p>Variables defined inside a function are <em>not accessible outside the function</em>. We say that function bodies have a <strong>local scope</strong>. This helps to keep your program easy to read and write: if you define a local variable, then you don't need to worry about it in the rest of the notebook.</p>
</li>
</ul>
<p>There are two other ways to group epxressions together that you might have seen before: <code>begin</code> and <code>let</code>.</p>
<h6>begin</h6>
<p><strong><code>begin</code></strong> will group expressions together, and it takes the value of its last subexpression. </p>
<p>We use it in this notebook when we want multiple expressions to always run together.</p>
<h6>let</h6>
<p><strong><code>let</code></strong> also groups multiple expressions together into one, but variables defined inside of it are <strong>local</strong>: they don't affect code outside of the block. So like <code>begin</code>, it is just a block of code, but like <code>function</code>, it has a local variable scope.</p>
<p>We use it when we want to define some local (temporary) variables to produce a complicated result, without interfering with other cells. Pluto allows only one definition per <em>global</em> variable of the same name, but you can define <em>local</em> variables with the same names whenever you wish!</p>
<div class="footnote" id="footnote-1"><p class="footnote-title">1</p><p>Even a function like </p>
<p><code>f(x) = return</code></p>
<p>returns <strong>one object</strong>: the object <code>nothing</code> â try it out!</p>
</div>
</blockquote>

width: 21px;">5</div></div><pre class=" CodeMirror-line " role="presentation"><span role="presentation"><span class="cm-string">&gt; ##### _**function**_ vs. _**begin**_ vs. _**let**_</span></span></pre></div><div style="position: relative;"><div class="CodeMirror-gutter-wrapper" style="left: -30px;"><div class="CodeMirror-linenumber CodeMirror-gutter-elt" style="left: 0px; width: 21px;">6</div></div><pre class=" CodeMirror-line " role="presentation"><span role="presentation"><span class="cm-string">&gt; Writing functions is a way to group multiple expressions (i.e. lines of code) together into a mini-program. Note the following about functions:</span></span></pre></div><div style="position: relative;"><div class="CodeMirror-gutter-wrapper" style="left: -30px;"><div class="CodeMirror-linenumber CodeMirror-gutter-elt" style="left: 0px; width: 21px;">7</div></div><pre class=" CodeMirror-line " role="presentation"><span role="presentation"><span class="cm-string">&gt; - A function always returns **one object**.[^1] This object can be given explicitly by writing `return x`, or implicitly: Julia functions always return the result of the last expression by default. So `f(x) = x+2` is the same as `f(x) = return x+2`.</span></span></pre></div><div style="position: relative;"><div class="CodeMirror-gutter-wrapper" style="left: -30px;"><div class="CodeMirror-linenumber CodeMirror-gutter-elt" style="left: 0px; width: 21px;">8</div></div><pre class=" CodeMirror-line " role="presentation"><span role="presentation"><span class="cm-string">&gt; - Variables defined inside a function are _not accessible outside the function_. We say that function bodies have a **local scope**. This helps to keep your program easy to read and write: if you define a local variable, then you don't need to worry about it in the rest of the notebook.</span></span></pre></div><div style="position: relative;"><div class="CodeMirror-gutter-wrapper" style="left: -30px;"><div class="CodeMirror-linenumber CodeMirror-gutter-elt" style="left: 0px; width: 21px;">9</div></div><pre class=" CodeMirror-line " role="presentation"><span role="presentation"><span class="cm-string">&gt; </span></span></pre></div><div style="position: relative;"><div class="CodeMirror-gutter-wrapper" style="left: -30px;"><div class="CodeMirror-linenumber CodeMirror-gutter-elt" style="left: 0px; width: 21px;">10</div></div><pre class=" CodeMirror-line " role="presentation"><span role="presentation"><span class="cm-string">&gt; There are two other ways to group epxressions together that you might have seen before: `begin` and `let`.</span></span></pre></div><div style="position: relative;"><div class="CodeMirror-gutter-wrapper" style="left: -30px;"><div class="CodeMirror-linenumber CodeMirror-gutter-elt" style="left: 0px; width: 21px;">11</div></div><pre class=" CodeMirror-line " role="presentation"><span role="presentation"><span class="cm-string">&gt; </span></span></pre></div><div style="position: relative;"><div class="CodeMirror-gutter-wrapper" style="left: -30px;"><div class="CodeMirror-linenumber CodeMirror-gutter-elt" style="left: 0px; width: 21px;">12</div></div><pre class=" CodeMirror-line " role="presentation"><span role="presentation"><span class="cm-string">&gt; ###### begin</span></span></pre></div><div style="position: relative;"><div class="CodeMirror-gutter-wrapper" style="left: -30px;"><div class="CodeMirror-linenumber CodeMirror-gutter-elt" style="left: 0px; width: 21px;">13</div></div><pre class=" CodeMirror-line " role="presentation"><span role="presentation"><span class="cm-string">&gt; **`begin`** will group expressions together, and it takes the value of its last subexpression. </span></span></pre></div><div style="position: relative;"><div class="CodeMirror-gutter-wrapper" style="left: -30px;"><div class="CodeMirror-linenumber CodeMirror-gutter-elt" style="left: 0px; width: 21px;">14</div></div><pre class=" CodeMirror-line " role="presentation"><span role="presentation"><span class="cm-string">&gt; &nbsp; &nbsp; </span></span></pre></div><div style="position: relative;"><div class="CodeMirror-gutter-wrapper" style="left: -30px;"><div class="CodeMirror-linenumber CodeMirror-gutter-elt" style="left: 0px; width: 21px;">15</div></div><pre class=" CodeMirror-line " role="presentation"><span role="presentation"><span class="cm-string">&gt; We use it in this notebook when we want multiple expressions to always run together.</span></span></pre></div><div style="position: relative;"><div class="CodeMirror-gutter-wrapper" style="left: -30px;"><div class="CodeMirror-linenumber CodeMirror-gutter-elt" style="left: 0px; width: 21px;">16</div></div><pre class=" CodeMirror-line " role="presentation"><span role="presentation"><span class="cm-string">&gt; </span></span></pre></div><div style="position: relative;"><div class="CodeMirror-gutter-wrapper" style="left: -30px;"><div class="CodeMirror-linenumber CodeMirror-gutter-elt" style="left: 0px; width: 21px;">17</div></div><pre class=" CodeMirror-line " role="presentation"><span role="presentation"><span class="cm-string">&gt; ###### let</span></span></pre></div><div style="position: relative;"><div class="CodeMirror-gutter-wrapper" style="left: -30px;"><div class="CodeMirror-linenumber CodeMirror-gutter-elt" style="left: 0px; width: 21px;">18</div></div><pre class=" CodeMirror-line " role="presentation"><span role="presentation"><span class="cm-string">&gt; **`let`** also groups multiple expressions together into one, but variables defined inside of it are **local**: they don't affect code outside of the block. So like `begin`, it is just a block of code, but like `function`, it has a local variable scope.</span></span></pre></div><div style="position: relative;"><div class="CodeMirror-gutter-wrapper" style="left: -30px;"><div class="CodeMirror-linenumber CodeMirror-gutter-elt" style="left: 0px; width: 21px;">19</div></div><pre class=" CodeMirror-line " role="presentation"><span role="presentation"><span class="cm-string">&gt; </span></span></pre></div><div style="position: relative;"><div class="CodeMirror-gutter-wrapper" style="left: -30px;"><div class="CodeMirror-linenumber CodeMirror-gutter-elt" style="left: 0px; width: 21px;">20</div></div><pre class=" CodeMirror-line " role="presentation"><span role="presentation"><span class="cm-string">&gt; We use it when we want to define some local (temporary) variables to produce a complicated result, without interfering with other cells. Pluto allows only one definition per _global_ variable of the same name, but you can define _local_ variables with the same names whenever you wish!</span></span></pre></div><div style="position: relative;"><div class="CodeMirror-gutter-wrapper" style="left: -30px;"><div class="CodeMirror-linenumber CodeMirror-gutter-elt" style="left: 0px; <p>Alright! Every time that we run the simulation, we get slightly different results, because it is based on randomness. By running the simulation a number of times, you start to get an idea of the <em>mean behaviour</em> of our model. This is the essence of a Monte Carlo method! You use computer-generated randomness to generate samples.</p>

<p>In this exercise we will <em>re-use</em> our simulation infrastructure to study the dynamics of a different type of infection: there is no immunity, and hence no "recovery" rather, susceptible individuals may now be <strong>re-infected</strong> </p>
<h4>Exercise 4.1</h4>
<p>ð Make a new infection type <code>Reinfection</code>. This has the <em>same</em> two fields as <code>InfectionRecovery</code> (<code>p_infection</code> and <code>p_recovery</code>). However, "recovery" now means "becomes susceptible again", instead of "moves to the <code>R</code> class. </p>
<p>This new type <code>Reinfection</code> should also be a <strong>subtype</strong> of <code>AbstractInfection</code>. This allows us to reuse our previous functions, which are defined for the abstract supertype.</p>
